**Cho Yoon-beom:** He gave them all names. Characters inside him. Like Eusebius and Florestan.

132
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:35,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** Do they appear when he writes?

133
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:40,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He wrote under those names. He composed under those names, or used them as titles.

134
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:52,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** A sensitive literary boy with musical talent. After losing everyone he bonded with around the same time during his growth, he regressed.

135
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:08,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** But since he had a strong literary background, he tried to turn that into works. He expressed it through art forms like writing and music.

136
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:13,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Among musicians, he's probably recognized as the best writer.

137
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:18,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** A literary boy who could also perform?

138
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:23,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He was a good performer. He wanted to be a pianist originally.

139
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:43,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** But with a face like that... I suddenly understand this guy. He was born with artistic sensitivity and delicacy. Then tragedies struck like fate. But looking in the mirror, he sees a Greco-Roman wrestler. In this case, one either can't date at all or becomes extremely obsessed with it.

140
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:58,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** It's the latter. He had to fill the void. What's more intense than romance?

141
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:09,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** His portrait when he was older is Greco-Roman, but he was quite slender when young.

142
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:20,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** The frame is there. I think I know what kind of person he was. I'll understand better after hearing the music. So his mother sent him to law school?

143
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:23,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Yes, to Leipzig.

144
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** Where was he born?

145
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:28,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Zwickau.

146
00:18:29,000 --> 00:19:10,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** Zwickau is a small town. Most people wouldn't know it. It was in East Germany. About the distance between Seoul and Daejeon from Dresden. There was a car called Trabant there, the national car of East Germany. Known for extremely poor performance and lowest durability. But the exterior was pretty. Right after the opening of the Eastern Bloc in '90, '91, '92... I went to Dresden and saw the Trabant for the first time. It was so pretty. But the exhaust smoke! I really wanted to buy it. The shape is classic, but the inside is trash. The factory was in Zwickau.

147
00:19:31,000 --> 00:20:03,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Anyway, he went to Leipzig for university. But he hated law more than anything. There's almost no record of him attending classes. He signed up for lessons instead. He went to a music teacher, asking for piano lessons. There was a very famous teacher then, Friedrich Wieck, who made many people famous. Schumann learned piano under him. While taking lessons, he wanted to become a great pianist, so he used a strange machine on his fingers that was popular then.

148
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:06,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** A machine?

149
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:15,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** A machine made of cigar boxes. Like a pulley, it ties the fingers and has sandbags attached like an IV. He kept lifting his fingers.

150
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:19,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** For finger training. Like finger dumbbells.

151
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:27,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** On the piano, if you don't lift your fingers enough, you accidentally press other keys.

152
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:30,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** What do you know about piano? Please explain. Finger torture?

153
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:59,400
**Kim Ka-ram:** We say playing the piano well requires independent muscles for each of the ten fingers. Like athletes, the muscles need training. But the muscles attached to the hands are fine, not large muscles. So we do training to develop those muscles. For example, when I was young, to increase the power of my fingertips, I would put thick English dictionaries in a shoe bag and hang it while practicing.

154
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:03,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** On your fingers?

155
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:06,800
**Kim Ka-ram:** No, on my wrists. Then gravity pulls the weight down.

156
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** On your wrists?

157
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:16,600
**Kim Ka-ram:** Yes. In that state, I practiced lifting and lowering my fingers. Not hanging it on the fingers.

158
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** But Schumann hung it on his fingers.

159
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:23,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** That's too much.

160
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:41,200
**Cho Yoon-beom:** It wasn't an official method. It was unofficial, like a back-alley method. A back-alley finger dumbbell. He picked it up somewhere. He was doing finger lifts. His teacher saw him practicing like that and told him to stop. 'You'll ruin your muscles.' He did ruin them.

161
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** So his career as a pianist ended then?

162
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:57,200
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He was frustrated. It wasn't like 'you can't play at all', but he gave up on becoming a famous pianist. His finger function declined. He tried rehabilitation, but it didn't work.

163
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:59,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** Are there people like that among pianists?

164
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:15,200
**Kim Ka-ram:** Fingers are one thing, but there are things like neck discs. We practice for hours sitting without a backrest, leaning forward. We keep using our bodies, so it's physically demanding. After turning 40, some people can't perform due to physical strain.

165
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** But hanging dumbbells on fingers...

166
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:31,000
**Kim Ka-ram:** That's too much.

167
