**Kim Eo-jun:** I know this. This is Schumann. Master, why were you leaning to the left while playing?

235
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:09,000
**Kim Ka-ram:** I don't know why I do that either.

236
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:18,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** When she started, her body leaned about 10 degrees to the left. She didn't sit straight, she was crooked.

237
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:24,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** You didn't know yourself?

238
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:33,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** She's not always crooked. She was crooked for this one. For most of the performance, she was leaning to the left.

239
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:37,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Because she's a progressive performer.

240
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:39,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** Is she left-wing?

241
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:52,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** There were two features this time. One, the harmony changed in the middle, right? She smiled then. Then, what should I say... like nursing?

242
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:08,600
**Kim Ka-ram:** Right. This is Kinderszenen. A child's dream, not an adult's. A child dreaming while being nursed. I played it with that feeling.

243
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:40,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** But why did you nurse towards the left? Hearing this, I felt he was a lonely person. It felt sad. Like you said, his emotional growth might have stopped at 15. Regressive sensitivity. That feeling of being comfortable, safe, and surrounded by loved ones back then. He doesn't have that now. So he's lonely and misses it. It was sad knowing that. I think I'm sensitive.

244
00:36:54,000 --> 00:37:14,800
**Kim Ka-ram:** That's right. Schumann found it difficult to interact with others, and the only ones he felt comfortable with were children. He probably wanted to keep going back to himself as a child or a 10-year-old. But he couldn't, so he was lonely. He was left alone in the adult world.

245
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:31,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He originally wanted to do music and grow while being praised. But now he's running a magazine, promoting others. He introduced Chopin and Brahms, but nobody was praising him.

246
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:39,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** He gave others the praise he wanted to receive.

247
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:48,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He can't perform anyway. He wants to be recognized for composition, but he doesn't get proper recognition.

248
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:55,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** That 'Scherzo' would have been hard to applaud back then.

249
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:08,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** He didn't write things that people would like. When people suggested writing trendy things, he said, 'I can't write that.' Furthermore, his contemporaries considered him very conservative.

250
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:11,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** Why?

251
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:24,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Liszt and Wagner were emerging then. They were the self-proclaimed progressives. 'Music of the future!' But here's a magazine editor-in-chief occasionally composing in the old Beethoven style. They branded him a conservative.

252
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:45,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** Like a film critic making a short film and people saying he's doing it as a hobby. They accepted him like that. 'Oh, you can write and compose too?'

253
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:01,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** But ironically, most of the musicians who attacked Schumann were originally discovered by Schumann's magazine.

254
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:17,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** Doesn't matter. They were in different classes. They were orthodox musicians, and he was just a critic attached to them. Sideways. Then he wasn't recognized as an orthodox musician, and he was overshadowed by his wife.

255
00:46:21,000 --> 00:47:07,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** For example, he praised Chopin in his magazine, so Chopin came to see him. He didn't come for the editor-in-chief, but for his wife. 'Oh, this is Clara.' And Liszt, a huge womanizer back then, came and hit on Clara. It caused a rift between Schumann and Liszt. Later, they were on opposite sides: Wagner and Liszt on one side, and Schumann, his friend Mendelssohn, and Brahms on the other. Remember the 100-year war in music history? They were completely split. Schumann was the founder of the Brahms school. Liszt was on the other side. They were already on bad terms because of his wife. Liszt even dedicated a piece to Clara Schumann.

256
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:35,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** Dedicating it because she wouldn't fall for him. They only knew how to use music, so they dedicated it. It's nothing. I find those 'dedications' funny. They just used what they knew how to do. I look down on 'dedicated to someone' type of things. Who is today's last song dedicated to?

257
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:43,200
**Cho Yoon-beom:** A song dedicated to his wife.

258
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:46,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** To his wife? How long after?

259
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:49,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** It came out right after they got married.

260
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:59,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** He dedicated it to himself then. It was originally a song. Schumann successfully married at 30 after winning the trial. For three years after marriage, songs poured out.

261
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:06,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** Must have been the happiest time in his life.

262
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:42,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Uniquely, he dealt with one genre per year. Songs in the first year, symphonies in the second, chamber music in the third. So it's called the Year of Song, Year of Symphony, Year of Chamber Music. He made a songbook called Myrthen. Myrthen is the name of a flower. Used in a bride's wreath. One of the songs there is 'Widmung' (Dedication). Originally a song, but today we'll hear a piano version. Who transcribed it? Liszt. They were still on good terms then. So it's Schumann's melody but has Liszt's flashy piano style.

263
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:50,800


264
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:47,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** Master Kim Ka-ram felt it a lot this time.

