00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:53,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** It's so cool.

266
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:19,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** I like this too. The melodies heard in between are Schumann's, and the flashy arpeggios surrounding them are Liszt's style. I feel it through Master Kim Ka-ram. This time, she mostly played in the middle, moving like a pendulum. I felt compassion for Schumann. Like, 'Oh, you felt that way then? Yes, I know. I'll play that for you.' I felt that in her heart.

267
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:46,800
**Kim Ka-ram:** Thank you. Compassion is the right word. It's one of the happiest moments in his life, and a beautiful melody.

268
00:53:49,000 --> 00:54:04,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** 'I know what that is, so I'll play it for you.' That kind of feeling. Then, at the end, her butt slightly lifted from the chair. About 5cm. She sat back down. Why did you do that?

269
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:36,600
**Kim Ka-ram:** In music terms, there's 'sforzando'. It means to emphasize that part. There's also 'fortepiano', which means the same thing but requires a different expression. Schumann's difference between the two is very unique. For 'fortepiano', you could emphasize it like 'WAHK!' or like 'WA-AH'. I tried to express it like 'WA-AH'. If you see from the side, you'll understand why I momentarily shifted my weight and sat back.

270
00:54:51,000 --> 00:55:09,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Fortepiano means making it loud then immediately soft. You can go 'WA-AH' and decrease the volume, but this isn't a string instrument. Once you hit the key, it's done. Key hit, and that's it. So to express that with the body, she did that motion.

271
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:13,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** Using the whole body to express 'WA-AH'?

272
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:27,600
**Kim Ka-ram:** Yes, shifting weight slightly. For string instruments, you're still bowing, so loud to soft is possible. For us, it's over after the hit. So I try to put that expression into that moment as much as possible.

273
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:57,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** Desperate heart. It's like using your body when playing billiards. The ball is already hit, but you move your body to control the direction. Body Shinero. The ball is going, you can't influence it anymore, but you use body Shinero. Blowing energy into it, 'To the left, to the left!' Since I'm putting emotion into it, at least. Is there a term 'body Shinero' in piano performance?

274
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:19,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** That's incredible. It's not in the score, but performers interpret it that way. 'This is body Shinero'.

275
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:52,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** Please add that to the terminology. It hits home. sound is gone, but the heart remains. Putting a curve on the sound. You have to see it all together. And you understand the music after knowing Schumann's story. Without knowing, listening to the music alone is pointless. Those who appreciate it like that are fakes. Not exactly fakes, but we listen more deeply. I understand the music after knowing how Schumann lived and seeing Master Kim Ka-ram's performance. It's heart-wrenching. What happened next?

276
00:57:32,000 --> 00:59:06,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Liszt transcribed this, right? Liszt came over and said, 'I don't know why people in Leipzig, like Mendelssohn, are so conservative.' The couple got angry and said, 'Let's not see that guy again.' They saw him again later, of course, but they split like that. Schumann went to Düsseldorf. A beautiful place. He spent his later years there. He became the director of the Lower Rhenish Music Festival, which Mendelssohn used to direct. But he was very ill. Not just mentally, but he would shiver and couldn't sleep. Eventually, he said, 'Honey, maybe I should consult a mental hospital.' Clara was shocked. While it was getting worse, he was gone one day while she was out. He had packed his things and jumped into the Rhine. Suicide attempt. A passing sailor saved him. When he came to, he thought, 'What am I doing?' He had moved from the 5th floor to the 2nd floor before, fearing he might jump. Bipolar disorder. He went to the hospital voluntarily. Visitation was forbidden. Especially for his wife, as she was pregnant. Mental hospitals back then were truly inhumane. They couldn't see family. 2.5 years without seeing family. In the hospital, Schumann confessed, 'Actually, when I was young, I slept with the housekeeper at Professor Wieck's and got a disease.' Syphilis. He was treated with arsenic back then. He claimed his depression and physical symptoms started after that treatment.

277
00:59:53,000 --> 01:00:23,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** So after 2.5 years, she came. With Brahms. They were close and stayed so until he went to the hospital. Clara relied on Brahms a lot. After 2.5 years, they came together. Schumann must have sensed it. They left him for a moment to see others, and he was dead when they returned. He died right on the day Clara and Brahms came to visit him after 2.5 years? Right after the visit?

278
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:34,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Right after.

279
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:55,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** They killed him. How could he die on that exact day by coincidence? Clara and Brahms are having an affair. Brahms said he loves her, but she's married. Brahms said he can't betray the teacher who made him famous. Let's settle this. How could he die on the day they visited after 2.5 years?

280
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:31,000
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Clara said in an interview that his last words were 'I know everything'.

281
01:01:33,000 --> 01:02:02,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** He knew about her and Brahms! Musically, it's interpreted as 'I understand how hard it's been for you', but it's BRAHMS! He said 'I know everything' and then they killed him. They probably hesitated after the visit was allowed. 'Let's send him off.' Clara must have suggested it. Brahms might have hesitated, but she's a famous, beautiful pianist, and he's in love. If he comes out, it's over. So they did it?

282
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:25,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** A visit means he could recover and come out.

283
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:34,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** There are no hospital records of how he died, right?

284
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:39,600
**Cho Yoon-beom:** There are various theories, like tertiary syphilis.

285
01:02:41,000 --> 01:03:18,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** They probably made a deal with the hospital. 'Let's say he died of a chronic illness.' I forgot our host used to do political broadcasting. Think about it. What are the odds? Dying on the day of the visit after 2.5 years. The investigation didn't proceed, and the hospital handled it. 'He died of a chronic illness.' The hospital director probably got some money. Doctor, musician, everyone involved. Clara was desperate. What if her husband comes out again? And Brahms is in love with her. So, did they end up together?

286
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:40,200
**Cho Yoon-beom:** Clara lived for another 40 years.

287
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:41,000
**Kim Eo-jun:** Where is justice?

288
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:48,200
**Cho Yoon-beom:** I said Brahms was gaslighted by Clara for his whole life.

289
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:57,400
**Kim Eo-jun:** I said that without knowing this. Clara manipulated Brahms. Clara was smart. Fighting! Digity and practicality. A smart woman.

290
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:27,800
**Cho Yoon-beom:** One more thing. She hid the cause of her husband's death for a long time.

291
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:37,600
**Kim Eo-jun:** She took care of herself and her husband cleanly. But it started with revenge. He imprisoned her when she was young. He took half of her life.

292
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:47,000
**Kim Ka-ram:** Maybe, because she wanted to escape her father.

293
01:12:47,000 --> 01:13:09,800
**Kim Eo-jun:** She was trapped in the cage of 'Schumann's wife' when she knew nothing. It wasn't happy. For the 2.5 years he was in the hospital, she had no income, so she performed a lot to survive. She solved it economically. She's a person who can survive alone. She didn't want to miss the hard-earned chance.

294
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:28,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** If it wasn't a broadcast, I'd go all the way. 'I'll go alone.' Clara performed a lot to earn money during those 2.5 years. In Korea, there's a famous classic club, 'Schumann and Clara'.

295
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:43,200
**Kim Eo-jun:** How do they understand the relationship?

296
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:51,400
**Cho Yoon-beom:** A passionate love story. Suing and everything. They probably don't have stories about poison. Our host is the first.

